<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[189,310,409,435]" box="[189,310,409,435]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,409,435]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,409,435]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[188,1399,456,661]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Easily recognized from all congeners by the following characters: dorsum dirty pale brown, with an orange brown head and pronotal collar, and dark brown scutellum (
<figureCitation box="[966,1059,492,518]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="43.[189,232,1894,1920]" captionTargetBox="[255,1348,414,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-12@43.[189,1398,376,1856]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Fig. 2. Habitus of Ernestinus, Harpedona and Lopidolon spp. A. Ernestinus mimicus Distant, 1911, ♂, UASB. B. Ernestinus ramkeshariae Yasunaga &amp; Ishikawa, 2016, ♂, UASB. C. Harpedona sanguinipes Distant, 1904, ♂, UASB. D. Harpedona vittlaensis sp. nov, ♀, UASB. E–F. Lopidolon dandeliensis sp. nov., UASB. E. ♂. F. ♀." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690366" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690366/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
); pronotum heavily punctate, distinctly transverse, about 1.7× as wide as long, with an indistinct impressed line behind calli; labium long, reaching at least IV abdominal segment, apex of segment III surpassing hind coxa; genital capsule without spinelike processes and complex sclerotization on dorsal wall, with large, lobate ventral process (
<figureCitation box="[197,306,634,661]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="57.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[302,1333,446,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-53@57.[189,1398,408,1890]" captionTargetPageId="57" captionText="Fig. 16. Male genitalia of Harpedona vittlaensis sp. nov., holotype, UASB. A. Genital capsule in lateral view. B–C. Left paramere in dorsal and lateral views. D–E. Right paramere in dorsal and lateral views. F. Aedeagus in lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690397" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690397/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 16A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
